Bring a large #pot{} of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim @scallions{2}. Thinly slice greens; cut whites into 1⁄2-inch batons. Gently
crush @peanuts{1/2%ounce} in their bag.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain and set aside.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; thinly
slice crosswise into strips. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Swap in pork chops for chicken, cooked to an internal temperature of 165°.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat.
Add chicken in an even layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and
cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Transfer chicken to a #plate{}; wipe out pan.

Heat another drizzle of cooking oil in pan used for chicken over medium-high
heat. Add scallion whites, @coleslaw mix{4%ounce}, @garlic powder{1%tsp},
salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies begin to soften,
~{1-2%minutes}.

Return chicken to pan with veggies.

Add @sweet soy glaze{4%tbsp}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, @water{1/3%cup},
and as much @Sriracha{1%tsp} as you like; stir to combine.

Add drained noodles and half the peanuts to pan; remove from heat. Stir in
@butter{1%tbsp}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide lo mein between shallow #bowls{}. Sprinkle with scallion greens and
remaining peanuts. Serve.

> Poultry is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.